# Cursor Rules — Fantasy Cycling Tracker

## Role
You are an expert Next.js and Python developer building a fantasy cycling analytics web app. Always read CONTEXT.md before starting any task. It contains the full data model, API endpoints, auth flow, and business logic.

## Core Principles

### 1. Read before you build
Always check CONTEXT.md and existing files before writing new code. Never assume structure — verify it.

### 2. Stay on track
This is a focused analytics tool. Do not add features, pages, or complexity that are not described in CONTEXT.md or explicitly requested. If unsure, ask before building.

### 3. One thing at a time
Complete and test one feature fully before moving to the next. Do not scaffold everything at once and leave it half-finished.

### 4. Simple over clever
Prefer readable, simple code over clever abstractions. This codebase may be extended to a football scouting tool later, so keep logic modular and well-commented.

---

## Tech Stack Rules

### Next.js
- Use App Router (not Pages Router)
- API routes go in `/app/api/`
- Use server components where possible, client components only when needed (interactivity)
- Use `fetch` with proper error handling in all API routes

### Python
- Python scripts live in `/scripts/`
- Each script has a single responsibility (e.g. `fetch_holdet.py`, `parse_pcs.py`, `match_riders.py`)
- All scripts must handle errors gracefully and return structured JSON output
- Use `httpx` for HTTP requests, `beautifulsoup4` for HTML parsing
- Always normalize rider names before matching (see CONTEXT.md for normalization function)

### Supabase
- Use the service key (not anon key) for server-side writes
- Use the anon key for client-side reads only
- Always handle Supabase errors explicitly — never silently fail
- Follow the schema in CONTEXT.md exactly — do not add or rename columns without asking

### Styling
- Use Tailwind CSS
- Keep UI clean and functional — this is an analytics tool, not a marketing site
- Tables should be sortable and filterable
- Use green/yellow/red colors consistently for form flags (🟢🟡🔴🆕)

---

## Data & Business Logic Rules

### Never change these rules without asking:
- A rider "participated" in a race ONLY if `points > 0` in the after-snapshot
- Popularity alone does NOT indicate participation
- Form score = latest × 3 + second latest × 2 + third latest × 1
- Only races where `points > 0` count toward averages, totals, and trends
- Always use the normalization function from CONTEXT.md when matching PCS names to Holdet IDs

### Holdet Auth:
- Never hardcode credentials — always use environment variables
- Store session token securely — never expose it to the client
- Handle token expiry gracefully with a clear error message in the UI

---

## File Structure
```
/app
  /page.tsx                  # Dashboard
  /race-preview/page.tsx     # Race Preview
  /analyse/page.tsx          # Full analysis
  /admin/page.tsx            # Data management (fetch buttons)
  /api
    /fetch-holdet/route.ts   # Calls Python fetch_holdet.py
    /fetch-pcs/route.ts      # Calls Python parse_pcs.py
    /riders/route.ts         # Read riders from Supabase
    /snapshots/route.ts      # Read snapshots from Supabase
/scripts
  fetch_holdet.py            # Login + fetch players from Holdet API
  parse_pcs.py               # Scrape + parse PCS startlist HTML
  match_riders.py            # Match PCS names to Holdet IDs
  analyse.py                 # Calculate metrics (form score, avg, trend etc.)
/lib
  supabase.ts                # Supabase client setup
  types.ts                   # TypeScript types matching DB schema
CONTEXT.md                   # Always read this first
.cursorrules                 # This file
.env.local                   # Never commit this
```

---

## What NOT to do
- Do not use Pages Router
- Do not use any ORM (use Supabase SDK directly)
- Do not add authentication to the web app itself — it is a personal tool
- Do not add unnecessary npm packages — keep dependencies minimal
- Do not modify the database schema without updating CONTEXT.md first
- Do not use `any` type in TypeScript — always type properly
- Do not silently swallow errors — always surface them in the UI or logs
